postcontent:
Made by CTC Defense (the military arm of "Crimson Trace"), this is the Infrared laser that was selected by the Naval Special Warfare for the HK45c.  As such, the laser is not visible to the naked eye but is intended for use with night vision goggles.  The regular (visible) laser for the Heckler and Koch 45c is simply the LG-645 made by Crimson Trace.

I bought this for my 45c, but then decided the NVG route was much too expensive for me at this point in life, so my loss is your gain. These are no longer being made and the IR version is extremely difficult to find. 

This laser is brand new (never installed), with original (opened) packaging.  

I can text or email pictures on request (Nine Two Zero, 538 Three 171).

I will ship nationally, but will not ship overseas due to restrictions on IR lasers.

title: For Sale:  Edged Weapon Lessons
postcontent:
I am a 20 year practitioner and 8 year instructor specializing in impact and edged weapons.  
Many people who have CHP/CCW carry a knife or other short range tool, but have no idea how to use them.  If you carry such items as part of your EDC, you need this training.  Additionally, the tactics and techniques learned apply to the gun as well.  This training is meant to enable you to get home safely and without breaking the law.  I address the "why" and "when", not just the "how".  

Training topics include: 

- When to use a knife in self defense 
- The Citizen's Rule of Engagement
- Use of Force Case study: People Vs. Umali
- The 026 context 
- Precontact management
- Defensive language
- Basic combatives to access
- Point and edge methods
- Manipulation

At the end of the instruction the participant will:: 

- Gain a familiarity with the legal use of edged weapons in a civilian context
- Gain basic manipulation skills
- Gain a familiairty with precontact management skills
- Gain a understanding of the 026 concept
- Gain a familiarity with basic combatives to access methodology

Instruction will be conducted at your home or at Poor Richard's meeting space. 
The entire block of instruction is 2 hours.  
Individual instruction (one on one) is $40.  
LEO (including retired) and Military (active, AGR, NG, R, and veterans) train for free.  
Small group (no official affiliation) rates are available (6 participant limit, $30 per student)
Seminars for institutions/martial arts schools/organizations ($25 per participant, host trains for free)

Other subjects can be addressed, such as countering knife attacks, fight plans vs. active shooters, etc, email ot text to (719) 304 - 6764.  

Visit my site at https://026training.wordpress.com/

I do not offer training to individuals or groups affiliated with extremist views or hateful perspectives.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Sears Long Range Winner 12 Gauge (early 1900s)
location: Fort Mill, Rock Hill, South Carolina
postcontent: I've had since I was a kid, been sitting in the back of my safe and need to make some room.  The Sears Long Range Winner was made in the early 1900s by a handful of companies, including Crescent, Meriden and Stevens.  Due to the markings (AF&Co. on butt plate) I believe this one to be Andrew Fryberg & Company, who made them for Sears, prior to the formation of Meriden.  Which dates the gun to bout 1910.  I hadn't shot it, in a very long time (not since a kid, hunting rabbits), but mechanically it is still sound and in decent shape, considering being over 100 years old.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1842 Pattern Austrian Musket - Civil War Era
postcontent:
For sale is an Austrian Musket imported to the U.S. during the Civil War. These muskets were originally tubelock weapons, and were converted to percussion cap upon their arrival to the U.S. - mostly imported by the North, the South managed to get their hands on a few. This musket is interesting in that it was not converted for a musket cap, as would have been the standard. Rather, it is fitted for a number 11 cap. This implies a few things. One, that it was a civilian conversion, or two, that it was a Confederate conversion. Civilian is the more likely scenario, but there is no way to be certain.

The musket is in .70 caliber and is smoothbore. Everything works. The hammer cocks back and comes down strong. The musket can be fired, but I do not recommend it. I fired it around ten times with a very light charge of 45 grains, and it does shoot. However, there is a gap somewhere in the lock where some gas escapes out of the bottom. Not enough to be dangerous (again, I fired it like this without incident), but enough for me to recommend against firing it.

The musket is dated 1853. There are unit/regiment markings on the buttplate and tang, but I do not know if they refer to Austrian or American military.
Asking $450. Willing to negotiate to a certain extent.

Purchased this gun new about two months ago and never fired it - I immediately stripped it down and began the process of grip reduction/stippling. I used the heat method to reduce the grip, I rounded some of the edges on the frame, undercut the trigger guard, re-contoured the the finger grooves, and molded the factory 4th gen beavertail.
